(define-lesson mod-position-sys1-nat
    :step ((:p "In terms of " (:strong "understanding") ", adding and
    subtracting " (:q "longer") " numbers is " (:strong "no
    different") " than what you have already seen.  In order to
    understand what we are doing when we add or subtract, We can still
    use the 2 basic ideas of: "
    (:ol (:li "pairing things with a numberline number")
         (:li "measuring an amount with the numberline."))
    "We have also already seen how we can add numbers which are bigger
    than digits.") (:p "The " (:strong "only") " purpose
    of " (:strong "this") " lesson is to show you an efficient way of
    arranging your work when you add or subtract " (:q "longer") "
    numbers."))

    :step ((:p "If the numbers we are adding or subtracting
    are " (:q "long") ", with many digits in them, then we may become
    confused when we add or subtract the corresponding digits in the
    numbers.  For this reason, it can be useful to write the second
    and any following numbers " (:strong "under") " the first, so the
    corresponding digits are " (:strong "in line") " with each
    other.") (:p "Doing this just makes it easier
    to " (:strong "see") " which digits should be added together."))

    :step ((:p "In the next page a sum and a " (:q "hints") " button
    will replace this text, and a " (:q "sum editor") " will appear on
    your screen.") (:p "The " (:q "sum editor's") " menu is for
    writing numbers and symbols onto the square grid, which is like
    squared paper.  You can either use the keyboard or click on the
    menu using your mouse.") (:p "If you use the menu, the green keys
    are for writing things onto the grid and blue keys are for moving.
    The arrows change the direction in which you move.") (:p "If you
    select the " (:q "hints") " button, the tutor will make
    suggestions about what you should do, and give you help along the
    way.") (:p "You should practice, until you can do the sum without
    hints." ))

    :using-q&a-vars
